import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOSHUA = {
    "15": {
        "1": "<p>Judah's lot is first and largest among the tribal allotments — a priority that reflects Genesis 49:8-12: 'Judah, your brothers shall praise you... The scepter shall not depart from Judah, nor the ruler's staff from between his feet, until tribute comes to him; and to him shall be the obedience of the peoples.' The territorial primacy of Judah in the land distribution is a spatial prophecy: this is the tribe from which the Lion of Judah will come (Rev 5:5). The lot (<em>goral</em>) cast before YHWH is not random chance but providential arrangement; 'The lot is cast into the lap, but its every decision is from the LORD' (Prov 16:33). Christ's birth in Bethlehem of Judah (Matt 2:1) fulfills what the lot of Judah geographically ordained.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The southern boundary of Judah — from the tip of the Salt Sea — traces the edge of the territory that will eventually become the heart of the Davidic kingdom. The Salt Sea (Dead Sea) is the lowest point on earth, the place of death and barrenness. That Judah's inheritance borders the Dead Sea carries the typological pattern: the inheritance of the redeemed encompasses even the places of death. Christ descended into the lowest depths of human experience (Phil 2:7-8, 'he emptied himself... becoming obedient to the point of death, even death on a cross') so that his inheritance might include even those who dwell in death's shadow. 'I will ransom them from the power of Sheol' (Hos 13:14).</p>",
        "3": "<p>The boundary turns northward through the wilderness of Zin, Kadesh-barnea, Hezron — names that carry wilderness memories. Kadesh-barnea was the site of Israel's great failure (Num 13-14) where the spies' faithless report condemned a generation to death. That Judah's southern border passes through Kadesh-barnea means the territory of Judah encompasses the place of failure and shame. Christ's inheritance similarly encompasses the places of human failure: 'The Son of Man came to seek and to save the lost' (Luke 19:10). He did not choose an inheritance bounded only by the high and holy places; he crossed through Kadesh-barnea, through the sites of human betrayal and failure, to claim them for his kingdom.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The boundary continues to the Brook of Egypt (Wadi el-Arish) and the Great Sea — the Mediterranean coastline. The Great Sea as Judah's western boundary types the expanse of Christ's inheritance reaching to the ends of the earth: 'Ask of me, and I will make the nations your heritage, and the ends of the earth your possession' (Ps 2:8). The brook that forms the southwestern boundary was traditionally the boundary between Egypt and Canaan — Christ's inheritance begins exactly where Egypt ends, at the point of the completed exodus. Those in Christ have crossed the brook that separates slavery from freedom, and they stand in an inheritance that reaches to the Great Sea of the nations.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The eastern boundary of Judah — the Salt Sea — and the northern boundary's anchor at the Jordan River's mouth place Judah between the waters of death (Salt Sea) and the waters of crossing (Jordan). The allotted territory is bounded by the two great spiritual markers of Israel's history: the Jordan (the crossing into the inheritance) and the Dead Sea (the boundary of the desolate). Christ's inheritance is similarly defined by these two waters: his baptism in the Jordan inaugurated his messianic identity; his descent into death's domain (the lowest reaches) established the full scope of his redemption. Between Jordan and Dead Sea is the territory where YHWH's salvation history occurs — the same territory that bounds Judah's inheritance.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The boundary goes up to Beth-hoglah and passes along north of Beth-arabah — 'house of the crossing' and 'house of the plain' or 'house of desolation.' The territory of Judah includes both the places of crossing (Beth-hoglah, 'house of the partridge,' near the Jordan crossing) and the places of desolation (Arabah, the arid wilderness). Christ's inheritance encompasses both the places of miraculous crossing and the places of wilderness desolation. As the Son of Man who was tempted in the wilderness (Matt 4:1) and who crossed through death and resurrection, his territorial claim includes both the Jordan fords and the desolate plains of human experience.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The boundary goes up to Debir from the Valley of Achor. The Valley of Achor ('Valley of Trouble') was where Achan was stoned for his theft at Jericho (Josh 7:24-26) — the valley of Israel's most famous individual sin and its punishment. That Judah's boundary passes through the Valley of Achor is theologically significant: the inheritance of the promised people passes through the valley of trouble and judgment. Hosea 2:15 promises that in the restoration, YHWH will 'make the Valley of Achor a door of hope.' Christ transformed the valley of trouble into the door of hope by bearing in himself the judgment that Achan received — 'He himself bore our sins in his body on the tree' (1 Pet 2:24).</p>",
        "8": "<p>The boundary climbs to the shoulder of the Jebusite city (Jerusalem) on the south — Jerusalem first appears in Joshua's tribal allotments as a boundary marker not yet possessed, defined by a people (Jebusites) who would not be expelled until David's conquest (2 Sam 5:6-9). Jerusalem's presence at the boundary of Judah's territory as an unsubdued city types the 'not yet' of eschatological possession: the city of the great King (Ps 48:2; Matt 5:35) is identified and promised but not yet fully possessed until the appointed king comes. As David eventually captured the Jebusite stronghold and made it his capital, Christ will fully possess the heavenly Jerusalem (Heb 12:22; Rev 21:2) at his return.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The boundary drawn to the spring of the waters of Nephtoah — the fresh-water spring that marks the boundary between Judah and Benjamin — types the living water that marks the boundary of the new covenant's inheritance. Jesus's offer of living water at Jacob's well (John 4:10-14: 'whoever drinks of the water that I will give him will never be thirsty again — the water that I will give him will become in him a spring of water welling up to eternal life') recasts the spring at Nephtoah as a type of the Spirit. The boundaries of Christ's kingdom are not set by boundary stones and survey lines but by the presence of the living water he gives — wherever the Spirit flows, the inheritance has been claimed.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The boundary continues to Mount Seir and Chesalon — 'Seir' (hairy, rough) and 'rolling' (if from <em>kasal</em>) carry the rough terrain of the boundary marking. The mountainous, difficult nature of the boundary territory types the hard-won nature of Christ's inheritance: 'For the kingdom of heaven has been coming violently, and the violent take it by force' (Matt 11:12). The inheritance is not awarded to the passive but to those who follow the leader through difficult terrain. As the boundary markers traverse difficult terrain, the path of discipleship passes through places that are hairy and rough — 'through many tribulations we must enter the kingdom of God' (Acts 14:22).</p>",
        "11": "<p>The boundary goes out to the shoulder of Ekron — Ekron, one of the five Philistine cities, is on the edge of Judah's territory. The Philistine city system (Gaza, Ashdod, Ashkelon, Gath, Ekron) borders Judah throughout the Judges and Samuel periods and represents the chronic 'enemy at the gate' — never fully expelled, always threatening. Goliath came from Gath; Samson's conflicts were with the Philistines; David fought the Philistines throughout his career. That Ekron appears on Judah's boundary types the principalities and powers that border the inheritance of the redeemed — always present on the boundary, never fully expelled in this age, awaiting the final conquest. Christ has defeated the principalities (Col 2:15), but the final expulsion awaits (1 Cor 15:24-26).</p>",
        "12": "<p>The Great Sea and its coastline forms the western boundary of Judah — 'this is the boundary of the people of Judah all around according to their clans.' The sea as boundary is the limit of the known world in Israel's geography; beyond the Great Sea is the unknown. Christ's inheritance is bounded in this age by the sea — 'make disciples of all nations' has the sea as its horizon, the unreached peoples beyond the known world. Revelation's new creation removes even this boundary: 'the sea was no more' (Rev 21:1) — the boundary of the unknown, the limit of the inheritance, is removed when the new earth is established. What was the western limit of Judah's inheritance in this age is abolished in the consummation.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Caleb's portion is given 'according to the commandment of YHWH to Joshua' — Joshua grants Caleb his inheritance based on a divine command given at Kadesh-barnea forty-five years earlier (Num 14:24: 'But my servant Caleb, because he has a different spirit and has followed me fully, I will bring into the land into which he went, and his descendants shall possess it'). Caleb waited forty-five years for a promise made at the moment of crisis. This patience types the believer who holds the promise through the wilderness period: 'So do not throw away your confidence, which has a great reward. For you have need of endurance, so that when you have done the will of God you may receive what is promised' (Heb 10:35-36). Caleb received what was promised; the one who perseveres to the end will receive the crown of life (Rev 2:10).</p>",
        "14": "<p>Caleb drove out the three sons of Anak from Hebron — Sheshai, Ahiman, and Talmai. The sons of Anak were the 'giants' that had so terrified the faithless spies forty years earlier (Num 13:28,33). Caleb's conquest of the very enemy that had broken Israel's nerve types the believer's victory over the fears that once paralyzed them — and more specifically, types Christ's victory over death, the ultimate giant. 'Since therefore the children share in flesh and blood, he himself likewise partook of the same things, that through death he might destroy the one who has the power of death, that is, the devil, and deliver all those who through fear of death were subject to lifelong slavery' (Heb 2:14-15). Caleb's personal conquest of the Anakim types Christ's personal defeat of death's champion.</p>",
        "15": "<p>From Hebron, Caleb goes up against Debir (formerly Kiriath-sepher, 'city of the scroll/book'). Caleb attacks the 'city of the book' — and captures it. The conquest of Kiriath-sepher types Christ's claim over all human knowledge and wisdom: 'In him are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge' (Col 2:3). The 'city of the scroll' that was the intellectual center of pre-conquest Canaan fell to YHWH's faithful servant. As every Canaanite stronghold — including the city of books — belonged to the inheritance, so 'every thought' is to be taken 'captive to obey Christ' (2 Cor 10:5). No domain of human knowledge stands outside Christ's inheritance; all wisdom ultimately belongs to the one in whom all wisdom dwells.</p>",
        "16": "<p>'Whoever strikes Kiriath-sepher and captures it, to him will I give Achsah my daughter as wife' — Caleb's offer of his daughter for the conquest of the book-city introduces the Achsah narrative. The marriage-prize for military victory is a type of the eschatological marriage of Christ and the church: those who participate in Christ's conquest receive the bride (in the Achsah type, become the bridegroom by receiving the bride). Othniel, who wins Achsah, becomes Israel's first judge (Josh 3:9-11) — the first deliverer/savior figure after Joshua. The pattern of conquest → marriage → deliverer-judge types Christ: he conquers, claims his bride, and delivers his people.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Othniel son of Kenaz, Caleb's brother, took Kiriath-sepher and received Achsah. Othniel is the first judge of Israel after Joshua — the first in the cycle of apostasy-oppression-cry-deliverance that structures Judges. His appearance here as the winner of Achsah's hand establishes him as the prototypical deliverer: he wins the bride through conquest, not birthright. Christ wins his bride the same way — not through natural inheritance but through conquering death. 'Husbands, love your wives, as Christ loved the church and gave himself up for her, that he might sanctify her... so that he might present the church to himself in splendor, without spot or wrinkle' (Eph 5:25-27). Othniel's winning of Achsah is the first instance of this bridal-conquest pattern in the promised land.</p>",
        "18": "<p>When Achsah came to Othniel, she urged him to ask her father Caleb for a field — then she herself dismounted from her donkey and asked Caleb: 'Give me a blessing. Since you have given me the land of the Negeb, give me also springs of water.' The daughter approaching the father to ask for a blessing she needs — springs to make the dry Negeb fruitful — types the believer's intercession before the Father through Christ. Jesus's own invitation is this Achsah-pattern: 'Ask, and it will be given to you; seek, and you will find; knock, and it will be opened to you' (Matt 7:7). As Caleb freely gives what his daughter asks, so the Father freely gives what his children ask: 'If you then, who are evil, know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will your Father who is in heaven give good things to those who ask him!' (Matt 7:11).</p>",
        "19": "<p>'Give me a blessing. Since you have given me the land of the Negeb, give me also springs of water.' Caleb gave her the upper springs and the lower springs. The Achsah narrative is the OT's most explicit water-inheritance type. The daughter received land (the Negeb — dry, southern territory), but land without water is death; she asked for and received springs. Jesus's conversation with the Samaritan woman recasts this precisely: 'If you knew the gift of God, and who it is that is saying to you, \"Give me a drink,\" you would have asked him, and he would have given you living water' (John 4:10). The upper and lower springs type the full blessing of the Spirit — both the heavenly (upper) and earthly (lower) dimensions of the Spirit's presence. The request for springs becomes the pattern of prayer for the Spirit: 'Ask the Father in my name, and he will give you another Helper' (John 14:16).</p>",
        "20": "<p>'This is the inheritance of the tribe of the people of Judah according to their clans' — the summary formula closes the opening section and introduces the district-by-district city lists. The inheritance summary types the NT's summary of Christ's inheritance: 'In him we have obtained an inheritance, having been predestined according to the purpose of him who works all things according to the counsel of his will' (Eph 1:11). The tribal inheritance 'according to their clans' distributes the one possession into many particular portions — as the one inheritance in Christ is distributed into many particular callings, gifts, and places: 'To each is given the manifestation of the Spirit for the common good' (1 Cor 12:7). The one inheritance diversified into particular possessions.</p>",
        "21": "<p>The city lists of Judah's Negeb district (vv.21-32) — twenty-nine cities distributed across the southern territory — type the detailed specificity of Christ's inheritance. The inheritance is not abstract but particular: each city has a name, a location, a history. As each city in the Negeb district was a specific place where specific people lived under YHWH's covenant, so each member of Christ's body is a specific person with a specific calling. 'But as it is, God arranged the members in the body, each one of them, as he chose' (1 Cor 12:18). The twenty-nine Negeb cities are not interchangeable dots on a map but distinct places — as the members of the body are distinct persons, each with irreplaceable function.</p>",
        "22": "<p>Kinah and Dimonah and Adadah — names largely unknown in later biblical history. The 'small' cities of the inheritance, the ones that never appear in another narrative, are not therefore less inherited. Christ's inheritance includes the obscure as fully as the famous: 'There is neither Jew nor Greek, there is neither slave nor free, there is no male and female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus' (Gal 3:28). The cities no one knows about are as fully within Judah's inheritance as Jerusalem and Bethlehem. The obscure members of the body are as fully part of Christ as the prominent ones: 'On the contrary, the parts of the body that seem to be weaker are indispensable' (1 Cor 12:22).</p>",
        "23": "<p>Kedesh, Hazor, Ithnan — Kedesh means 'holy place'; Hazor (which appears in Joshua's military campaign, ch11) now appears as a settlement within the inheritance. The Hazor that was burned and destroyed (11:11-13) becomes a named possession within Judah's territory. What was a site of violent judgment in the conquest becomes a settled inheritance in the allotment — the movement from judgment to possession types the eschatological pattern: 'For behold, I create new heavens and a new earth, and the former things shall not be remembered or come into mind' (Isa 65:17). The destroyed city becomes an inherited settlement; the judged creation becomes the new creation.</p>",
        "24": "<p>Ziph and Telem and Bealoth — the Ziph of the Negeb district (v.24) is distinct from the hill-country Ziph (v.55) where David hid from Saul. The appearance of 'Ziph' twice in Judah's list types the pattern of Christ's appearing: he came first in humility (the Ziph where David hid, the incarnation in obscurity) and will come again in glory (the Ziph of the inheritance fully possessed). The same name, two appearances — as the one Christ who came in weakness will come again in power. The Ziphites betrayed David's hiding place to Saul; the world opposed the incarnate Christ; but in the final possession, the territory of betrayal becomes inherited land.</p>",
        "25": "<p>Hazor Hadattah and Kerioth-hezron — Kerioth appears in later prophetic literature as a place of judgment (Jer 48:24; Amos 2:2). The appearance of Kerioth in Judah's city list alongside the promise of inheritance creates a typological tension: places associated with future judgment are nonetheless within the territory of the inheritance. This types the 'already-not-yet' of Christ's kingdom: even the places not yet fully redeemed are within the scope of the inheritance, claimed by the Lord of all the earth but not yet fully transformed. The judgment on Kerioth (Moab's Kerioth) does not negate Judah's Kerioth; YHWH's judgment and YHWH's inheritance are both real, operating on different dimensions.</p>",
        "26": "<p>Amam, Shema, Moladah — Moladah (<em>moledah</em>, birth/lineage) reappears in the Simeonite list (19:2) and after the exile (Neh 11:26). The word 'lineage' embedded in a place name within Judah's inheritance types the birth-from-above theology of the NT: the inheritance belongs to those with the right lineage — but the right lineage is not biological but spiritual. 'But to all who did receive him, who believed in his name, he gave the right to become children of God, who were born, not of blood nor of the will of the flesh nor of the will of man, but of God' (John 1:12-13). The city of 'lineage' within Judah's inheritance is inherited by those born of God.</p>",
        "27": "<p>Hazar-gaddah, Heshmon, Beth-pelet — the <em>chatzar</em> (enclosed hamlet) place names that dominate the Negeb list reflect the pastoral, village character of the southern inheritance. Christ's inheritance is not only the great cities but the small hamlets, the enclosed communities, the places of simple life. The kingdom of heaven is like a mustard seed (Matt 13:31-32) — small and enclosed at first, but destined to become a great tree. The <em>chatzar</em> hamlets of Judah's southern inheritance type the apparently small and insignificant communities of believers that the kingdom gathers: 'God chose what is low and despised in the world, even things that are not, to bring to nothing things that are' (1 Cor 1:28).</p>",
        "28": "<p>Beer-sheba appears in Judah's city list — the great patriarchal city where Abraham dug the well of the oath (Gen 21:31-32) and where Jacob received his theophany on the way to Egypt (Gen 46:1-4). The appearance of Beer-sheba within the tribal inheritance confirms that the patriarchal promises have been fulfilled in the allotment. Christ is the fulfillment of every patriarchal promise: 'For all the promises of God find their Yes in him' (2 Cor 1:20). The well of Beer-sheba (seven wells, the well of the oath) types the Spirit given by Christ: 'If anyone thirsts, let him come to me and drink' (John 7:37). Every patriarchal well of promise finds its fulfillment in the living water Christ provides.</p>",
        "29": "<p>Baalah, Iim, Ezem — Baalah (feminine of Baal) is a place-name that preserves Canaanite cultic geography within the tribal inheritance. The inheritance includes places that were formerly Baal-worship sites — reclaimed by inclusion within Israel's territory. This types Christ's reclamation of what was surrendered to idols: 'The silver is mine, and the gold is mine, declares the LORD of hosts' (Hag 2:8). Every place that had been surrendered to Baal-worship belongs by right to YHWH; the tribal allotment is an act of reclamation. Christ's inheritance similarly reclaims what sin and idolatry had captured: 'He has delivered us from the domain of darkness and transferred us to the kingdom of his beloved Son' (Col 1:13).</p>",
        "30": "<p>Eltolad, Chesil, Hormah — Hormah (<em>chormah</em>, devotion to destruction, H2763) is named for the <em>herem</em> — the sacred destruction of a site under YHWH's holy war. The appearance of Hormah in the city list means that a site once placed under the sacred ban is now a settled inheritance. The ban-site becomes a home. This types the transformation Christ accomplishes: what was under divine judgment becomes, through his atoning work, a place of habitation. 'For Christ also suffered once for sins, the righteous for the unrighteous, that he might bring us to God' (1 Pet 3:18). The <em>herem</em> that fell on the innocent Christ transforms what was under judgment into an inheritance for the redeemed.</p>",
        "31": "<p>Ziklag, Madmannah, Sansannah — Ziklag becomes David's base during his Philistine exile (1 Sam 27:6), given to him by Achish and remaining a royal Judahite possession. The trajectory of Ziklag — from Judahite city-list entry to exile-base for the hunted anointed king to royal possession — types Christ's trajectory: the territory given by the Father (the allotment) includes the places of suffering (the exile in Philistia, the cross) which become the royal inheritance through suffering. David's Ziklag was a place of humiliation before it was a royal possession; Christ's cross was the place of humiliation that became the throne of his royal inheritance (Rev 5:9-10).</p>",
        "32": "<p>Lebaoth, Shilhim, Ain, Rimmon — the closing formula, 'all the cities with their villages: twenty-nine' — the precision of the count types the precision of God's knowledge of his own. 'He knows those who are his' (2 Tim 2:19). Not one city is lost in the count; not one member of Christ's inheritance is unknown to him. 'I know my own and my own know me' (John 10:14). The twenty-nine Negeb cities with all their villages are enumerated before YHWH; the full number of the redeemed is known to the Father: 'Your Father who is in heaven is not willing that any of these little ones perish' (Matt 18:14). The exact count — not rounded up or estimated — types the divine precision of election.</p>",
        "33": "<p>The Shephelah district opens with fourteen cities — the foothills between the coastal plain and the Judean highlands. The Shephelah was the most contested zone of Judah's inheritance, the frontier where Israelite and Philistine power constantly clashed. That Judah's inheritance explicitly includes the contested frontier zone types Christ's claim over the most contested territories — the places where the powers most strenuously resist his lordship. 'The reason the Son of God appeared was to destroy the works of the devil' (1 John 3:8). The Shephelah, precisely because it was the zone of maximum conflict, was most fully included in the inheritance — the more contested the territory, the more clearly it belongs to Christ.</p>",
        "34": "<p>Eshtaol and Zorah — the twin towns of Samson's territory (Judg 13:2,25; 16:31). Samson, the strongest man in Israel and the most flawed of the judges, was buried between Zorah and Eshtaol. The territory of Samson within Judah's inheritance types the breadth of Christ's redemptive reach: Samson, with all his flaws, all his moral failures, all his spiritual inconsistency, is within the inheritance. Hebrews 11:32 includes Samson in the hall of faith. The places of the most compromised champions of YHWH are within the inheritance — as the most compromised believers are within Christ's body: 'Such were some of you. But you were washed, you were sanctified, you were justified in the name of the Lord Jesus Christ' (1 Cor 6:11).</p>",
        "35": "<p>Jarmuth and Adullam — Adullam, where David fled to the cave and gathered his band of desperate followers (1 Sam 22:1-2), is within Judah's inheritance. The cave of Adullam became the gathering place for 'everyone who was in distress, and everyone who was in debt, and everyone who was bitter in soul' (1 Sam 22:2) — the first followers of the anointed-but-rejected king. These types Christ's first followers: 'God chose what is foolish in the world to shame the wise; God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong; God chose what is low and despised in the world, even things that are not' (1 Cor 1:27-28). The cave at Adullam within the inheritance is Christ's kingdom gathering the distressed, indebted, and bitter.</p>",
        "36": "<p>Shaaraim, Adithaim, Gederah — Shaaraim ('two gates') appears in the Goliath narrative (1 Sam 17:52) as the place the Philistines fled toward after David's victory. The city of 'two gates' within Judah's inheritance types Christ as the gate of salvation: 'I am the door. If anyone enters by me, he will be saved and will go in and out and find pasture' (John 10:9). The Philistines fled through the 'two gates' in terror after the giant fell; those who flee to Christ through the door of faith find refuge. The place where the enemy fled becomes, within the inheritance, the place of safety for the Lord's own.</p>",
        "37": "<p>Zenan, Hadashah, Migdal-gad — Migdal (tower) appears repeatedly in Judean place names. The tower within the inheritance types Christ as the strong tower: 'The name of the LORD is a strong tower; the righteous man runs into it and is safe' (Prov 18:10). The city of the tower is not merely a defensible position but a place of refuge for those who run to YHWH's name. As each Migdal-town within Judah's inheritance provided a watchtower from which threats could be seen and enemies repelled, Christ as the divine name provides the height of perspective and safety from which his people see the enemy's approach and are protected.</p>",
        "38": "<p>Dilean, Mizpeh, Joktheel — Mizpeh (watchtower) is the name given to multiple towns throughout Israel, each marking an elevated position of watchfulness. The watchman image runs through the prophets: 'I have posted watchmen on your walls, O Jerusalem; they shall never be silent day or night' (Isa 62:6). The inheritance of the redeemed includes the watchpoints — the places of vigilance, the high ground from which the Lord's people see what is coming. Christ himself is the ultimate watchman: 'He who keeps Israel will neither slumber nor sleep' (Ps 121:4). The Mizpeh-towns within Judah's inheritance type the unceasing watchfulness of Christ over his people.</p>",
        "39": "<p>Lachish, Bozkath, Eglon — Lachish is the second most important city in Judah, eventually destroyed by Assyria (the Lachish reliefs in the British Museum) and among the last to fall to Babylon (Jer 34:7). The presence of Lachish in the tribal allotment, followed by its later conquest and destruction, carries the eschatological pattern: even the most strongly fortified cities within the inheritance are not permanent in this age. The inheritance of this age is partial and provisional; the final inheritance is imperishable. 'An inheritance that is imperishable, undefiled, and unfading, kept in heaven for you' (1 Pet 1:4) contrasts with Lachish, which fell to every conqueror. The earthly Lachish in Judah's allotment types what the heavenly Lachish (the new Jerusalem) will be.</p>",
        "40": "<p>Cabbon, Lahmas, Chitlish — the less-known cities of the second Shephelah district represent the ordinary interior of the inheritance: not the famous cities, not the contested frontier, but the agricultural hinterland where daily life unfolds. Christ's kingdom is primarily inhabited by the ordinary: 'Not many of you were wise according to worldly standards, not many were powerful, not many were of noble birth' (1 Cor 1:26). The inheritance is mostly Cabbons and Lahmasim — ordinary towns of ordinary people who together constitute the territory of YHWH's covenant. The inheritance is glorious not because its members are individually impressive but because they collectively belong to the King of kings.</p>",
        "41": "<p>Gederoth, Beth-dagon, Naamah, Makkedah — Beth-dagon (house of the grain deity) preserves a Canaanite name within Judah's inheritance. Makkedah is where Joshua executed the five Amorite kings who hid in the cave (Josh 10:16-17) — the cave of execution becomes a city within the inheritance. The place where YHWH's enemies were publicly judged becomes a settled possession of his people. Christ's cross was both the place of execution and the place of inheritance: 'Having disarmed the rulers and authorities, he put them to open shame, by triumphing over them in him' (Col 2:15). The cave at Makkedah where kings were hanged types Golgotha, where the powers were publicly shamed through the very instrument they thought was their victory.</p>",
        "42": "<p>Libnah, Ether, Ashan — Libnah (white) was a Levitical city (Josh 21:13) and later rebelled against Judah (2 Kgs 8:22). The 'white city' within the inheritance that later revolted types the constant tension between inherited position and lived faithfulness. The church is the 'holy nation' (1 Pet 2:9) by inheritance and calling, but its members struggle with the same tendency toward revolt. 'I am amazed that you are so quickly deserting the one who called you by the grace of Christ' (Gal 1:6). The inheritance is secure; the inhabitants' faithfulness is not. The security of the inheritance does not guarantee the faithfulness of those who inhabit it.</p>",
        "43": "<p>Iphtah, Ashnah, Nezib — names that appear only here in the biblical text. The once-named and never-again-mentioned cities of the inheritance are not therefore insignificant. Christ knows every name: 'I am the good shepherd. I know my own and my own know me' (John 10:14). The cities that appear only in Joshua 15's city list but nowhere else in the Bible are still fully within the inheritance; the people who live quiet, unrecorded lives are still fully known to the Good Shepherd. The obscurity of Iphtah and Nezib in the biblical record does not diminish their place in the inheritance — as the obscurity of most believers does not diminish their place in Christ.</p>",
        "44": "<p>Keilah, Achzib, Mareshah — Keilah was the city David rescued from the Philistines (1 Sam 23:1-5), only to have its inhabitants plan to hand him over to Saul (1 Sam 23:12). The city that was saved by the anointed king and then plotted against him types the ingratitude of those Christ saves who then turn against him. Yet Keilah remains within the inheritance — its potential betrayal does not remove it from the tribal territory. Christ's inheritance includes those who fail him; 'All we like sheep have gone astray; we have turned — every one — to his own way; and the LORD has laid on him the iniquity of us all' (Isa 53:6). The rescued city that became ungrateful is still within the inheritance Christ guards.</p>",
        "45": "<p>Ekron with its towns and villages — one of the five Philistine cities appears as a possession within Judah's territory, though the Philistines are never fully expelled from it. The partial possession of Ekron types the 'already-not-yet' of sanctification: territories claimed in principle are not always fully possessed in practice. 'For the desires of the flesh are against the Spirit, and the desires of the Spirit are against the flesh, for these are opposed to each other, to keep you from doing the things you want to do' (Gal 5:17). The inheritance claimed at baptism includes territory not yet fully subdued. The full expulsion of the Philistine from Ekron awaits the final parousia.</p>",
        "46": "<p>The stretch from Ekron to the sea — Ashdod and its towns and villages — the coastal Philistine territory formally within Judah's allotted portion but never fully possessed during the monarchic period. The Philistine coast types the most resistant zone of human culture to Christ's lordship — the places of power, commerce, and cultural dominance that resist spiritual conquest most persistently. Yet they are within the allotted inheritance; the claim is legitimate even when the possession is incomplete. Christ's commission — 'the ends of the earth' (Acts 1:8) — encompasses the most resistant cultures as fully as the most receptive.</p>",
        "47": "<p>Ashdod, its towns and villages; Gaza, its towns and villages, to the Brook of Egypt — Gaza, the southernmost Philistine city and one of Samson's contexts (Judg 16), is included in Judah's allotment. Gaza was never conquered during the biblical period of the tribal inheritance; it represents the promise that exceeds the current possession. In the NT, Gaza appears once: Philip is directed to 'the road that goes down from Jerusalem to Gaza' — to meet the Ethiopian eunuch, the first Gentile convert in Acts 8:26-39. The road to Gaza, which led to the inheritance's unrealized southern promise, became the route of the first breakthrough into the Gentile world. What was the unconquered limit of the tribal inheritance became the gateway for the gospel to the nations.</p>",
        "48": "<p>The hill country district opens Judah's central territory — eleven cities including Shamir, Jattir, Socoh. The mountains of Judah are the spiritual heartland: Jerusalem, Bethlehem, Hebron all lie in the hill country. Christ was born in the hill country (Bethlehem, Luke 2:4), presented in Jerusalem's temple hill (Luke 2:22), crucified on a hill (Golgotha, John 19:17), and ascended from the Mount of Olives (Acts 1:12). The entire drama of the first coming unfolds within the hill country of Judah. The inheritance given to Judah in the hill country is the stage on which the climax of salvation history occurs.</p>",
        "49": "<p>Dannah, Kiriath-sannah (Debir), Anab — Debir/Kiriath-sannah appears here as a hill country city, previously encountered as Kiriath-sepher ('city of the book') that Caleb offered as a marriage prize (15:15-16). The 'city of the book' within the hill country inheritance types the place of Torah in the inheritance: the written word of God at the center of the elevated territory. As the hill country's books and wisdom are within the inheritance, so the entire canon of Scripture belongs to Christ: 'These are written so that you may believe that Jesus is the Christ, the Son of God, and that by believing you may have life in his name' (John 20:31). The city of books in the hill country is claimed for the one of whom the books speak.</p>",
        "50": "<p>Anab, Eshtemoh, Anim — 'Anim' means 'springs,' another water-inheritance connection in the hill country. The hill country's springs type the sources of living water that flow from the inheritance: 'Out of his heart will flow rivers of living water' (John 7:38). The Spirit given by Christ flows from the elevated territory of the inheritance — the hill country of YHWH's presence — outward into the plains and valleys of the world. The springs of the hill country feed the lower regions; the Spirit given from the 'hill country' of Christ's ascended presence (the heavenly places) flows down to sustain life throughout the earth.</p>",
        "51": "<p>Goshen, Holon, Giloh — Goshen appears here as a hill country town in Judah, distinct from the Egyptian Goshen where Israel was enslaved. The reclamation of the name 'Goshen' — from a place of slavery (Egypt) to a settled inheritance in the hill country of Canaan — types the transformation Christ works in the redeemed: what was associated with bondage is now associated with freedom and inheritance. Paul's argument in Galatians 4:21-31 makes this reclamation explicit: the earthly Jerusalem corresponds to Hagar and slavery; the heavenly Jerusalem corresponds to Sarah and freedom. The inheritance is a new Goshen — the same name, but now a place of freedom rather than bondage.</p>",
        "52": "<p>Arab, Dumah, Eshan — Dumah means 'silence' and appears in Isaiah's oracle against Edom (Isa 21:11-12: 'the oracle concerning Dumah'). The city of Silence within the Judean hill country inheritance types the 'silence' of the land of death that Christ entered and broke open. 'He descended to the dead' (Apostles' Creed); he entered the silence of Sheol and announced the gospel there (1 Pet 3:19). The city of Silence within the inheritance is not silent forever — Christ speaks even in the silence of death. 'The hour is coming, and is now here, when the dead will hear the voice of the Son of God, and those who hear will live' (John 5:25).</p>",
        "53": "<p>Janum, Beth-tappuah, Aphekah — Beth-tappuah ('house of the apple') within the hill country inheritance carries the fragrance of the Song of Songs: 'As an apple tree among the trees of the forest, so is my beloved among the young men' (Song 2:3). The 'house of the apple' in Judah's hill country types the fruitfulness of the Beloved's dwelling — the place of the beloved in the inheritance is the fragrant, fruit-bearing house. Christ is the vine whose branches bear fruit (John 15:1-5); the inheritance is the vineyard where the Beloved's fruit grows. The city of the apple within the hill country types the fruitful fellowship of Christ and his own.</p>",
        "54": "<p>Humtah, Kiriath-arba (Hebron), Zior — Kiriath-arba, or Hebron, is the most important city in the hill country — the place of Abraham's covenant (Gen 13:18; 15:18), Sarah's burial (Gen 23), David's first capital (2 Sam 2:11), and Caleb's inheritance (Josh 14:13-14). The city of the fathers — the city of covenant memory — is at the heart of Judah's hill country inheritance. Christ came to Abraham's city, born of Abraham's seed, fulfilling the covenant made at Hebron/Mamre: 'Now the promises were made to Abraham and to his offspring. It does not say, \"And to offsprings,\" referring to many, but referring to one, \"And to your offspring,\" who is Christ' (Gal 3:16). Hebron in the inheritance is the city of the fulfilled Abraham-covenant.</p>",
        "55": "<p>Maon, Carmel, Ziph, Juttah — Maon and Carmel appear in the Nabal narrative (1 Sam 25): David sought food from Nabal of Maon, was refused, and was saved by Nabal's wife Abigail who became David's wife. The territory of the anointed king's rejection (Nabal refused David) and the territory of the provision given by the wise woman (Abigail brought food) are both within the inheritance. Christ similarly came to his own inheritance and was refused by many (John 1:11), but the 'Abigails' — those with wisdom to recognize the anointed king and provide for him — became his own. The inheritance includes both Nabal's refusal and Abigail's provision.</p>",
        "56": "<p>Jezreel, Jokdeam, Zanoah — Jezreel appears in multiple contexts (the valley, the city in Issachar) but here as a Judahite town. The name Jezreel means 'God sows' — a name of both judgment (Hos 1:4, the place of the blood of Jezreel) and restoration (Hos 2:22, 'the earth shall answer the grain, the wine, and the oil, and they shall answer Jezreel'). Hosea's transformation of Jezreel from a place of judgment to a place of sowing types Christ's transformation of the cross from execution to planting: 'Unless a grain of wheat falls into the earth and dies, it remains alone; but if it dies, it bears much fruit' (John 12:24). The city of 'God sows' within the inheritance is the place where divine judgment becomes divine harvest.</p>",
        "57": "<p>Kain, Gibeah, Timnah — Timnah appears in the Samson narrative (Judg 14) as the Philistine city where Samson chose his wife. The territorial intersection between Judah and Philistia at Timnah (on the boundary of Judah and Dan, Josh 19:43) types the place where the strongest man in Israel entered into dangerous covenant with the enemy. Christ himself entered into the most dangerous covenant — taking human flesh (the 'Philistine territory' of fallen humanity) — in order to destroy the enemy from within. 'Since therefore the children share in flesh and blood, he himself likewise partook of the same things, that through death he might destroy the one who has the power of death' (Heb 2:14).</p>",
        "58": "<p>Halhul, Beth-zur, Gedor — Beth-zur ('house of the rock') within the hill country types Christ as the rock of the inheritance: 'For they drank from the spiritual Rock that followed them, and the Rock was Christ' (1 Cor 10:4). The house built on the rock (Matt 7:24-25) types the inheritance founded on Christ: 'No one can lay a foundation other than that which is laid, which is Jesus Christ' (1 Cor 3:11). Beth-zur's location on the main road between Hebron and Jerusalem made it a key defensive position in the Maccabean period (1 Macc 4:29-34). The house of the rock within the hill country inheritance types the church's defensive security in Christ against every assault.</p>",
        "59": "<p>Maarath, Beth-anoth, Eltekon — Beth-anoth ('house of responses/echoes') within the hill country inheritance types the responsive community of worship that inhabits the inheritance: 'Speaking to one another in psalms and hymns and spiritual songs, singing and making melody to the Lord with your heart' (Eph 5:19). The 'house of responses' is the antiphonal worship community — as the hill country's echoes respond to each other across the valleys, so the worshiping community responds to YHWH's word with thanksgiving. The inheritance is not a silent territory but a singing one: 'He put a new song in my mouth, a song of praise to our God' (Ps 40:3).</p>",
        "60": "<p>Kiriath-baal (Kiriath-jearim), Rabbah — Kiriath-jearim is where the Ark of the Covenant rested for twenty years after its return from the Philistines (1 Sam 7:1-2), and where David came to bring it to Jerusalem (2 Sam 6:2). The city of the Ark's long sojourn — the place where YHWH's presence waited for the right king to come and claim it — is within Judah's hill country inheritance. Christ is the Ark's ultimate fulfillment: 'In him all the fullness of God was pleased to dwell' (Col 1:19). Kiriath-jearim, where the presence of God waited in the hill country for David, types the whole OT as the waiting-place of the divine presence that Christ finally came to bring into its full dwelling.</p>",
        "61": "<p>The wilderness district of Judah — six cities including Beth-arabah and Middin — comprises the Judean desert, the most desolate part of the inheritance. The wilderness within the inheritance is not excluded territory but claimed territory. Jesus himself spent forty days in this very wilderness (Matt 4:1-11), claiming the desolate places as the theater of his victory over temptation. The wilderness district within Judah's inheritance types the church's calling to inhabit and redeem the desolate places of human experience: 'The Spirit of the Lord GOD is upon me... to proclaim the year of the LORD's favor, and the day of vengeance of our God; to comfort all who mourn... to give them a beautiful headdress instead of ashes' (Isa 61:1-3).</p>",
        "62": "<p>Nibshan, the City of Salt, En-gedi — En-gedi ('spring of the kid') on the western shore of the Dead Sea is an oasis in the most desolate landscape of the inheritance. David hid in the caves of En-gedi when fleeing from Saul (1 Sam 23:29; 24:1) — the spring in the desert was the place of the anointed king's refuge. The Song of Songs uses En-gedi: 'My beloved is to me a cluster of henna blossoms in the vineyards of En-gedi' (Song 1:14). The spring in the wilderness where the beloved is found types Christ as the oasis in the desert of this age — living water in the most barren landscape. The wilderness district's En-gedi is the inheritance's preview of the 'springs of living water' that Christ gives (Rev 7:17).</p>",
        "63": "<p>'But the Jebusites, the inhabitants of Jerusalem, the people of Judah could not drive out, so the Jebusites dwell with the people of Judah at Jerusalem to this day' — the incomplete conquest of Jerusalem types the 'not yet' of Christ's kingdom in this age. Jerusalem, the city of the great King (Ps 48:2), is claimed but not fully possessed until the appointed king comes. David would take it (2 Sam 5:6-9); Christ will fully possess the heavenly Jerusalem at the consummation (Rev 21:2: 'I saw the holy city, new Jerusalem, coming down out of heaven from God'). The Jebusites dwelling in Jerusalem 'to this day' is Joshua's testimony that the inheritance is real but not yet fully actualized — the same testimony the church makes about every unredeemed aspect of the creation: claimed, not yet fully possessed.</p>",
    },
    "16": {
        "1": "<p>The lot of the sons of Joseph — Ephraim and Manasseh — begins at the Jordan near Jericho. The double portion of Joseph (Gen 48:5-6, Manasseh and Ephraim counted as two tribes) types the double blessing of the new covenant: 'And from his fullness we have all received, grace upon grace' (John 1:16). Joseph himself, who received the double portion by his father's special blessing, types Christ as the 'firstborn among many brothers' (Rom 8:29) through whom the double portion of grace flows. As Jacob transferred the birthright blessing from the firstborn (Reuben) to Joseph's sons, the Father transfers the fullness of blessing from the first Adam to those born again through Christ.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The border goes from Bethel to Luz — and the note that Bethel and Luz are two names for the same location (Gen 28:19, Jacob renamed it Bethel after the stairway vision) is embedded in the tribal boundary description. Bethel ('house of God') was the site of Jacob's dream of the stairway with angels ascending and descending (Gen 28:12) — which Jesus explicitly applies to himself: 'You will see heaven opened, and the angels of God ascending and descending on the Son of Man' (John 1:51). The boundary of Joseph's inheritance passes through the 'house of God' — the site of the first heaven-earth connection in Jacob's history — as Christ is himself the Bethel, the house of God made flesh, the true meeting point of heaven and earth.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The border goes down westward to the territory of Japhletites, to Lower Beth-horon — the Beth-horon passes (upper and lower) were key military corridors in Judah's history, where Joshua defeated the five Amorite kings (Josh 10:10-11) and where the 'sun stood still' miracle occurred. That the border of Joseph's inheritance runs through the Beth-horon pass means the inheritance is defined by the place of the greatest military miracle of the conquest. Christ's inheritance is similarly defined by the place of the greatest victory: 'He was delivered up for our trespasses and raised for our justification' (Rom 4:25). The border of the inheritance runs through the site of the decisive battle.</p>",
        "4": "<p>'The people of Joseph, Manasseh and Ephraim, received their inheritance' — the summary statement echoes Paul's summary of the new covenant inheritance: 'In him you also, when you heard the word of truth, the gospel of your salvation, and believed in him, were sealed with the promised Holy Spirit, who is the guarantee of our inheritance until we acquire possession of it, to the praise of his glory' (Eph 1:13-14). As Manasseh and Ephraim received their inheritance through Joseph, believers receive their inheritance through Christ. The guarantee-seal of the Spirit is the 'advance land survey' — the present experience of the Spirit as the down payment of the full inheritance yet to come.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The territory of Ephraim by their clans — the boundary that marks Ephraim's specific inheritance within the broader Joseph territory. The specificity of tribal boundaries within the broader inheritance types the specificity of spiritual gifts and callings within the broader body: 'Having gifts that differ according to the grace given to us, let us use them' (Rom 12:6). As each tribe received a distinct but complementary territory within the land, each member of the body receives distinct gifts and callings within the one inheritance. The boundary that defines Ephraim's territory does not diminish Manasseh's; the specific calling of one member does not diminish another's.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The border goes eastward to Taanath-shiloh — Shiloh, the central sanctuary of Israel's tribal period where the tabernacle rested (Josh 18:1) and where Hannah prayed for Samuel (1 Sam 1:9-11), is adjacent to Ephraim's territory. The proximity of Ephraim's border to Shiloh types the proximity of Christ's tribe (Judah) to the place of divine presence. But Shiloh itself ('the one to whom it belongs') is a messianic name: Genesis 49:10 promises 'until Shiloh comes, and to him shall be the obedience of the peoples.' The Shiloh near Ephraim's border is both a place (the central sanctuary) and a promise (the coming one to whom everything belongs). Christ is both the tabernacle presence and the 'Shiloh' to whom obedience flows.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The boundary goes down from Janohah to Ataroth and Naarah — 'Ataroth' means 'crowns.' The crown-city within Ephraim's inheritance types the royal glory that belongs to Christ and is shared with his people: 'To the one who conquers, I will grant him to sit with me on my throne, as I also conquered and sat down with my Father on his throne' (Rev 3:21). The crown-names embedded in the tribal territories point toward the diademed Christ (Rev 19:12: 'on his head are many diadems') who shares his royal inheritance with those who persevere. Ataroth in the inheritance is the advance echo of the crowns of the victorious.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The border goes westward to the brook Kanah and ends at the sea — the Mediterranean coast as the western limit of Ephraim's inheritance. As noted in Judah's allotment, the Great Sea as boundary types the universal scope of the inheritance that reaches to the 'ends of the earth.' Ephraim's specific western boundary is the same sea that bounds Judah's territory — different tribes share the same ultimate boundary, the sea of the nations. Christ's inheritance in the church does not divide the sea boundary into tribal sections; all streams of the church's mission flow toward the same horizon, the same commission to all nations.</p>",
        "9": "<p>'Together with the towns that were set apart for the people of Ephraim within the inheritance of Manasseh, all those towns with their villages' — the towns within Manasseh's territory set apart for Ephraim types the phenomenon of the smaller portion within the larger: the specifically appointed gift within the broader inheritance. Paul uses similar language: 'To each is given the manifestation of the Spirit for the common good... All these are empowered by one and the same Spirit, who apportions to each one individually as he wills' (1 Cor 12:7,11). The apportionment of specific towns within a brother's territory types the Spirit's specific apportionment of gifts — not by tribal formula but by divine will, creating interdependence within the inheritance.</p>",
        "10": "<p>'However, they did not drive out the Canaanites who lived in Gezer, so the Canaanites have lived in the midst of Ephraim to this day but have been made to do forced labor' — the failure to expel the Canaanites at Gezer and the compromise of forced labor types the persistent presence of sin's power in the believer's life. 'For I do not do what I want, but I do the very thing I hate' (Rom 7:15). The Canaanite in Gezer is subdued but not expelled — as sin in the believer is defeated in principle (through the cross) but not yet fully expelled (until the resurrection). 'The flesh desires against the Spirit' (Gal 5:17) — the Canaanite-in-Gezer condition describes the Christian experience between justification and glorification. The full expulsion awaits the final conquest.</p>",
    },
    "17": {
        "1": "<p>Manasseh's firstborn status — though Ephraim received the greater blessing (Gen 48:14-20) — and the allotment to Machir, 'the firstborn of Manasseh, the father of Gilead, because he was a man of war.' The warrior inherits the war-territories (Gilead and Bashan in Transjordan). The pattern types Christ as both firstborn and warrior: 'He is the image of the invisible God, the firstborn of all creation' (Col 1:15) and 'I am the first and the last... I have the keys of Death and Hades' (Rev 1:17-18). The warrior-firstborn who inherits the territories of conflict types Christ who, as the firstborn from the dead, inherits the domain of death itself — the very territory he conquered by entering it.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The rest of Manasseh's sons — Abiezer, Helek, Asriel, Shechem, Hepher, Shemida — received portions by their clans. The distribution of Manasseh's inheritance among his sons and daughters (the Zelophehad case follows) types the distribution of Christ's inheritance among his 'many brothers': 'For those whom he foreknew he also predestined to be conformed to the image of his Son, in order that he might be the firstborn among many brothers' (Rom 8:29). As Manasseh's sons each received their named portion, each member of Christ's family receives a specific, named inheritance: 'I go to prepare a place for you' (John 14:2) — not a generic residence but a prepared, specific place for each.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Zelophehad son of Hepher had no sons, only daughters — Mahlah, Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Tirzah. Their case had been adjudicated by Moses at YHWH's command (Num 27:1-11): daughters may inherit when there is no son. The daughters of Zelophehad are among Scripture's most remarkable figures of inclusion in the inheritance. They type those who receive the inheritance not through natural right (they had no brother) but through the specific provision of divine grace. 'In Christ Jesus you are all sons of God, through faith' (Gal 3:26) — those who had no natural claim to the inheritance (Gentiles, the spiritually disinherited) receive it through the specific provision of the Father through Christ.</p>",
        "4": "<p>'They approached Eleazar the priest and Joshua the son of Nun and the leaders and said, \"The LORD commanded Moses to give us an inheritance among our brothers.\" So according to the mouth of the LORD he gave them an inheritance among their father's brothers' — the daughters of Zelophehad appealed to the divine command given through Moses and received what was commanded. This types the believer's prayer of appeal to the Father through Christ: we come to the great high priest (Eleazar types Christ, Heb 2:17) and cite the divine promise: 'For all the promises of God find their Yes in him' (2 Cor 1:20). The daughters received their inheritance because they appealed to what YHWH had spoken; believers receive theirs through the same appeal to the divine word.</p>",
        "5": "<p>Ten portions fell to Manasseh besides the land of Gilead and Bashan — the larger tribal allocation reflecting the double-Joseph blessing. The ten portions distributed among Manasseh's descendants types the generosity of Christ's inheritance: 'His divine power has granted to us all things that pertain to life and godliness' (2 Pet 1:3). The one inheritance is generous, not stingy — it distributes ten portions and more. Paul's prayer for the Ephesians captures this abundance: 'That you may be filled with all the fullness of God' (Eph 3:19). The ten portions of Manasseh's inheritance are a spatial image of the fullness of what is given to those who are in Christ.</p>",
        "6": "<p>'Because the daughters of Manasseh received an inheritance along with his sons, and the land of Gilead was allotted to the rest of the people of Manasseh' — the daughters' inheritance alongside the sons within the same tribal allotment types the equality of the new covenant inheritance. 'There is neither Jew nor Greek, there is neither slave nor free, there is no male and female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus. And if you are Christ's, then you are Abraham's offspring, heirs according to promise' (Gal 3:28-29). The inheritance that the daughters of Zelophehad received alongside their uncles prefigures the new covenant's abolition of inheritance-distinctions based on natural status. All who are in Christ are heirs with equal standing before the Father.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The territory of Manasseh goes from Asher to Michmethath, which is east of Shechem — Shechem was the first place Abraham stopped in Canaan (Gen 12:6), where he built an altar and received the land promise. Shechem appears as a geographic reference point within Manasseh's territory — the original covenant site is now within the inherited land. The place where the covenant was first received has become the center of the inheritance. For those in Christ, the place of initial encounter with grace ('when I first believed') is not left behind but becomes the center from which the whole inheritance is measured. The Shechem of faith's origin is the pivot of the inheritance.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The land of Tappuah belonged to Manasseh, but the town of Tappuah on the boundary of Manasseh belonged to Ephraim — the town at the exact boundary belongs to a different tribe than the surrounding territory. This boundary-complexity types the overlapping nature of spiritual gifts and ministries in the body: some functions (the 'town') belong to a different expression of the body than the surrounding 'territory.' The same gift may flow through different streams of the church; the same ministry may be exercised across denominational or cultural boundaries. The boundary complexity of Tappuah types the Spirit's freedom to apportion gifts across the neat lines humans draw.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The boundary goes down to the brook Kanah — south of the brook the towns belonging to Ephraim amid the towns of Manasseh; the territory of Manasseh is on the north of the brook. The shared brook as boundary types the common source of life that flows through the distinctions of the body: 'For in one Spirit we were all baptized into one body — Jews or Greeks, slaves or free — and all were made to drink of one Spirit' (1 Cor 12:13). The brook Kanah flows through the boundary between Ephraim and Manasseh — one water source for two tribes, as one Spirit flows through the whole body of Christ regardless of the particular expression in which members are placed.</p>",
        "10": "<p>Ephraim to the south, Manasseh to the north — two halves of the Joseph inheritance flanking each other. Together they form the central hill country, the backbone of the land. This joint inheritance types the unity-in-diversity of the body: 'For just as the body is one and has many members, and all the members of the body, though many, are one body, so it is with Christ' (1 Cor 12:12). Ephraim and Manasseh together constitute 'Joseph's territory' in the same way that Jews and Gentiles together constitute 'Christ's body.' The two tribes are distinct (different boundaries, different histories) but one in their Joseph-origin — as the many members of the body are distinct but one in their Christ-origin.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Manasseh has — within Issachar and Asher — Beth-shean, Ibleam, Dor, En-dor, Taanach, and Megiddo. Beth-shean was where Saul's body was displayed after his death (1 Sam 31:10); Megiddo was where King Josiah was killed (2 Kgs 23:29-30) and where the final battle of Armageddon will be fought (Rev 16:16). The great cities of final judgment and ultimate battle are within the inheritance of Manasseh — types of the eschatological territory that Christ claims. Megiddo-Armageddon, the place of the last great conflict, is within the Lord's inheritance; the final battle is fought on territory the Lord owns. 'He must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet' (1 Cor 15:25) — including at Megiddo.</p>",
        "12": "<p>'Yet the people of Manasseh could not take possession of those cities, but the Canaanites persisted in dwelling in that land' — the fourth 'could not drive out' pattern in the allotment chapters (cf. 15:63; 16:10). The persistent inability to expel the Canaanites from key cities within the inheritance is a canonical pattern for the 'not yet' of eschatological possession. Christ's people possess the inheritance in principle (Eph 2:6: 'seated with him in the heavenly places') but not yet in its fullness. The Canaanite-in-the-inheritance types every dimension of the old creation that has not yet been transformed: 'We ourselves, who have the firstfruits of the Spirit, groan inwardly as we wait eagerly for adoption as sons, the redemption of our bodies' (Rom 8:23).</p>",
        "13": "<p>'When the people of Israel grew strong, they put the Canaanites to forced labor, but did not utterly drive them out' — the compromise of labor-subjugation rather than expulsion types the partial sanctification of this age. The Canaanite sin-pattern is not abolished but domesticated — put to use rather than expelled. This is the consistent pastoral problem the NT addresses: 'Do not use your freedom as an opportunity for the flesh' (Gal 5:13). The domesticated Canaanite who does forced labor but is not expelled types the flesh-pattern that is temporarily controlled but not mortified. 'Put to death therefore what is earthly in you' (Col 3:5) — the NT calls for expulsion, not merely subjugation.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'The people of Joseph spoke to Joshua, saying, \"Why have you given me but one lot and one portion as an inheritance, although I am a numerous people, since all along the LORD has blessed me?\"' — the Joseph tribes' complaint about their portion types the church's occasional perception that the inheritance given is insufficient for its size and calling. The complaint presupposes that numerical greatness requires more territory — a logic Christ inverts: 'Whoever would be great among you must be your servant' (Matt 20:26). The large tribe demanding more territory types the ambition of greatness that Christ consistently redirects. The blessed and numerous Joseph tribes needed not more territory but the courage to possess what was already given.</p>",
        "15": "<p>Joshua's response — 'If you are a numerous people, go up by yourselves to the forest, and there clear ground for yourselves in the land of the Perizzites and the Rephaim, since the hill country of Ephraim is too narrow for you' — types Christ's response to the disciples' ambition. 'The son of Man came not to be served but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many' (Matt 20:28). The way to a larger inheritance is through the hard work of clearing the forest, not through demanding a reallocation. The forest to be cleared types the spiritual work of discipleship and sanctification: 'Work out your own salvation with fear and trembling, for it is God who works in you' (Phil 2:12-13). The inheritance expands through obedient work, not through complaint.</p>",
        "16": "<p>'The hill country is not enough for us. Yet all the Canaanites who dwell in the plain have chariots of iron, both those in Beth-shean and its villages and those in the Valley of Jezreel' — the iron chariots are the overwhelming military obstacle that makes the Joseph tribes feel unable to possess their full inheritance. Iron chariots represent the apparently invincible power of the world's systems against which Christ's kingdom seems helpless. The Philistine military-technological advantage (iron weapons and chariots) was the great threat to early Israel. Christ's kingdom similarly faces the 'iron chariots' of political power, cultural dominance, and economic force. Yet 'the weapons of our warfare are not of the flesh but have divine power to destroy strongholds' (2 Cor 10:4). The iron chariot is not the final word.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Joshua's reply: 'You are a numerous people and have great power. You shall not have one allotment only, but the hill country shall be yours, for though it is a forest, you shall clear it and possess it to its farthest borders. For you shall drive out the Canaanites, though they have chariots of iron, and though they are strong' — the commission to drive out the iron-chariot Canaanites is a direct promise that what seems impossible is achievable. 'I can do all things through him who strengthens me' (Phil 4:13). Joshua's promise to the Joseph tribes carries Christ's tone of commissioned confidence: you have great power (from YHWH); the obstacle is real, but the promise is real too. The iron chariot is a reason to trust YHWH's power, not a reason to abandon the inheritance.</p>",
        "18": "<p>'For you shall drive out the Canaanites, though they have chariots of iron, and though they are strong' — the chapter closes on this commission, which is the last word in the allotment of Ephraim and Manasseh. The final word is not the iron chariot but the promise: you shall drive them out. As the book of Revelation closes with the promise that overcomes every apparent obstacle — 'Behold, I am making all things new' (Rev 21:5) — the allotment chapters close with a promise that overrides every 'could not drive out.' The iron chariot that seems invincible in chapter 17 is the same power that will be finally defeated when the Commander of YHWH's army returns. 'He must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet. The last enemy to be destroyed is death' (1 Cor 15:25-26).</p>",
    },
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('christ', 'joshua')
    merge_comm(existing, JOSHUA)
    save_comm('christ', 'joshua', existing)
    total = sum(len(existing.get(ch, {})) for ch in ['15','16','17'])
    print(f'ch 15-17: {total} verses in output')
    print('Joshua 15-17 christ commentary written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
